value.0: Brother Edmund takes care of the Temple supplies, if you need something, he knows where to find it. An aging Cleric in his early 60's, he moves with slow confidence and emits an air of warmth and tranquility. Lately, he has been educating the youth in the ward about physiology and botany.

This particular Templar has a pair of gloves sticking oddly out of his belt, as if they were placed there hastily or from an awkward angle. On closer inspection, the red color on them appears to be still-wet pant, and not simply the standard Salandran dye...

This Illuskan boy doesn't speak much, often keeps to himself even amongst the other orphans. The dedicated efforts of the Salandrans some of his peers, however, appear to be keeping him from becoming any more withdrawn in the aftermath of the war. An occasional, small smile might be hard won out of him.

A homely half-orc girl who seems to have developed a thick emotional skin. She seems to get along well with the other orphans, for the most part, despite occasional taunts and jabs. When there are minor disputes when the attention of the adults is elsewhere, she seems to be the one that intercedes to put an end to any bullying - often with just her presence alone.

This half-elven adolescent seems to be a trouble-maker of the group, but is equally adept at getting out of the trouble she gets herself in to. She is occasionally seen convincing the other children to do things on her behalf - usually something that will incite some harmless trouble. Blame rarely seems to stick to her.
This human adolescent has an empathetic demeanor about her, and might often be seen assisting the Salandrans with their chores and watching over the rest of those who lost their family in the war.

This seems to be some manner of educational game. It isn't entirely clear if their arrangement into the shape of a funny face is part of the game, or the work of a prankster.
A pair of adult-sized boots have been not-so-conspiciously abandoned here at the end of a trail of red paint tracks across the carpet.
These hands prints are in the same pigment as the red staining the carpet by the easels. The impression looks distended and strange, somehow...
